'''Ricardo Iv<U+00E1>n Rodr<U+00ED>guez Araya''' (born 25 August 1992) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full back|left back]] for [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in the [[Bundesliga]].

Born to a Spanish father and a Chilean mother, Rodr<U+00ED>guez began his  professional career at  local club [[FC Z<U+00FC>rich]] in 2010, having spent eight years in the youth setup. After breaking through into the first team at Z<U+00FC>rich, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was sold to [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in January 2012 for <U+00A3>7.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcz.ch/de/profis/news_archiv.htm?id=1514&page=98&ipp=10&archiv=1 |title=Ricardo Rodriguez wechselt definitiv zum VfL Wolfsburg |work=FC Z<U+00FC>rich |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=26 September 2014 |language=German }}</ref> He has been described as an accomplished defender and is noted for his strong heading ability.<ref name="Sky Sports" /> He has also become known for his ability to deliver pinpoint crosses.<ref name="FIFA Profile" /><ref name="FFT" /><ref name="Bleacher Report Scouting">{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1856748-scouting-reported-chelsea-transfer-target-ricardo-rodriguez |title=Scouting Report for Chelsea Transfer-Target Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Bleacher Report |date=19 November 2013 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez is also noted for his speciality in dead ball situations and for penalty taking abilities, emerging as Wolfsburg's first-choice penalty taker.<ref name="Bundesliga" /><ref name="Four Four Two" />

Rodr<U+00ED>guez has earned caps at every level of the Swiss national team setup, winning the [[FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA U17 World Cup]] in [[2009 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2009]]. A full international for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] since 2011, Rodriguez has earned over 25 caps for the country. He was part of the Swiss team at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] and later that year was voted [[Swiss Footballer of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2014/0000300753.php |title=Rodriguez wins Player of the Year Award |work=Bundesliga |date=2 September 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

==Club career==
===FC Z<U+00FC>rich===
Rodr<U+00ED>guez began playing football at the highly regarded youth club FC Schwamendingen in 2001 before joining  the youth setup of [[FC Z<U+00FC>rich]] as an 11-year-old in 2002.<ref name="Sky Sports" /> He was promoted to the senior squad in 2009 at age 16, making the bench for Z<U+00FC>rich's 2<U+2013>3 defeat to [[NK Maribor]] in the first leg of their [[2009<U+2013>10_UEFA_Champions_League_qualifying_phase_and_play-off_round#First_leg_3|third qualifying round]] Champions League tie on 29 July 2009.<ref name="Sky Sports" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000026/match=2000316/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Pavlovi<U+010D> puts Maribor in command |work=UEFA |date=29 July 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

He made his Z<U+00FC>rich debut as a 17-year-old in the 25th round of the [[2009<U+2013>10 Swiss Super League|Swiss Super League]] on 21 March 2010, replacing the injured [[Hannu Tihinen]] in the first-half of the 2<U+2013>0  win over [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2010/03/21/switzerland/super-league/fc-zurich/ac-bellinzona/893179/ |title=Z<U+00FC>rich vs. Bellinzona 2<U+2013>0 |work=Soccerway |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> His full debut came in the [[Z<U+00FC>rich Derby]] against [[Grasshopper Club Z<U+00FC>rich|Grasshoppers]] on 5 April, playing the entire 3<U+2013>2 win for the hosts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2010/04/05/switzerland/super-league/fc-zurich/grasshopper-club-zurich/893156/ |title=Z<U+00FC>rich vs. Grasshopper 3<U+2013>2 |work=Soccerway |date=5 April 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

He made only his second start in the first match of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Swiss Super League|Swiss Super League]] season on 20 July 2010, playing the full 90 minutes in a 2<U+2013>3 defeat to [[FC_Basel#Supporters_and_rivalries|rivals]] [[FC Basel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2010/07/20/switzerland/super-league/fc-basel/fc-zurich/947257/ |title=Basel vs. Z<U+00FC>rich 3<U+2013>2 |work=Soccerway |date=20 July 2010 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> On 28 April 2011, he scored his first professional goal for the club, opening the scoring for the hosts as they ran out 3<U+2013>0 winners over [[Neuch<U+00E2>tel Xamax]] at the [[Letzigrund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/04/28/switzerland/super-league/fc-zurich/neuchatel-xamax-fc/1057072/ |title=Z<U+00FC>rich vs. Neuch<U+00E2>tel Xamax 3<U+2013>0 |work=Soccerway |date=28 April 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

Rodr<U+00ED>guez made his [[UEFA competitions|European]] debut in the first-leg of their [[2011<U+2013>12_UEFA_Champions_League_qualifying_phase_and_play-off_round#First_leg_3|third qualifying round]] tie against [[Standard Li<U+00E8>ge]] on 27 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/teams/player=250011089/ |title=Ricardo Rodriguez |work=UEFA |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/07/27/europe/uefa-champions-league/standard-de-liege/fc-zurich/1155247/ |title=Standard Li<U+00E8>ge vs. Z<U+00FC>rich 1<U+2013>1  |work=Soccerway |date=27 July 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He played the entire match and provided the cross for fellow Z<U+00FC>rich youth team graduate [[Admir Mehmedi]] as the Swiss secured a 1<U+2013>1 draw at the [[Stade Maurice Dufrasne]] in Belgium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000261/match=2007529/postmatch/report/ |title=Gonz<U+00E1>lez goal saves the day for Standard |work=UEFA |date=27 July 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> In the second leg, Rodr<U+00ED>guez missed from an open goal from close range but Z<U+00FC>rich won 1<U+2013>0 to earn a spot in the play-off round against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000261/match=2007544/postmatch/report/index.html#mehmedi+books+zurich+berth |title=Mehmedi the hero as Z<U+00FC>rich march on |work=UEFA |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He played the entirety of both [[2011<U+2013>12_UEFA_Champions_League_qualifying_phase_and_play-off_round#Matches_4|play-off matches]] against Bayern,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/08/17/europe/uefa-champions-league/fc-bayern-munchen/fc-zurich/1182107/ |title=Bayern Munich vs. Z<U+00FC>rich 2<U+2013>0 |work=Soccerway |date=17 August 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/08/23/europe/uefa-champions-league/fc-zurich/fc-bayern-munchen/1182108/ |title=Z<U+00FC>rich vs. Bayern Munich 0<U+2013>1 |work=Soccerway |date=23 August 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> but the Swiss side fell 0<U+2013>3 on aggregate and dropped into the [[2011-12 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1657740.html |title=Gomez helps Bayern complete job against Z<U+00FC>rich |work=UEFA |date=23 August 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

On 26 October 2011, Rodr<U+00ED>guez scored his second goal for the club, netting his side's second from the penalty spot, in a 2<U+2013>0 win over [[FC Thun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/10/26/switzerland/super-league/fc-thun/fc-zurich/1116690/ |title=Thun vs. Z<U+00FC>rich 0<U+2013>2 |work=Soccerway |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> The club's final [[2011<U+2013>12 Swiss Super League|Super League]] match before the winter break on 10 December 2011, turned out to be Rodr<U+00ED>guez's last in a Z<U+00FC>rich shirt, playing the entire 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[FC Sion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/12/10/switzerland/super-league/fc-zurich/fc-sion/1116714/ |title=Z<U+00FC>rich vs. Sion 1<U+2013>1 |work=Soccerway |date=11 December 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> On 11 January 2012, Z<U+00FC>rich officials announced that the club had accepted a bid for Rodr<U+00ED>guez by German side [[VfL Wolfsburg|Wolfsburg]] and that he was on the verge of completing the transfer, subject to a medical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/11/transfer-zone/2012/01/11/2842356/zurichs-ricardo-rodriguez-poised-to-sign-for-wolfsburg?ICID=AR |title=Zurich's Ricardo Rodriguez poised to sign for Wolfsburg |work=Goal.com |date=12 January 2012 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> Despite being sold mid-way through the season, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was voted as the Fans' Player of the Season on 4 June 2012, ahead of [[Oliver Buff]] and [[Pedro Henrique Konzen|Pedro Henrique]].<ref name="FCZ">{{cite web|url=http://www.fcz.ch/de/profis/news_archiv.htm?id=1709&archiv= |title=Fanclub Letzi: Rodriguez ist Spieler der Saison |work=FC Z<U+00FC>rich |date=4 June 2012 |accessdate=23 September 2014 |language=German }}</ref>

===VfL Wolfsburg===
====Early career====
[[VfL Wolfsburg]] purchased Rodr<U+00ED>guez as a 19-year-old on 13 January 2012 for <U+00A3>7.5 million with the player signing a four and a half year deal.<ref name="Four Four Two" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/11/transfer-zone/2012/01/13/2845205/official-wolfsburg-sign-ricardo-rodriguez-from-zurich |title=Official: Wolfsburg sign Ricardo Rodriguez from Zurich |work=Goal.com |date=13 January 2012 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He quickly asserted himself into the first-team lineup, making his Bundesliga debut the next day against [[1. FC K<U+00F6>ln]], a 1<U+2013>0 victory for the Wolves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2011-12/18/1143447/spielanalyse_vfl-wolfsburg-24_1-fc-koeln-16.html |title=Polter vers<U+00FC><U+00DF>t Magaths Deb<U+00FC>tantenball |work=Kicker |date=21 January 2012 |accessdate=22 September 2014 |language=German }}</ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez went on to play every game of the season from that point on without being substituted, becoming a favorite on the left of the defense for manager [[Felix Magath]].<ref name="Sky Sports" />

Through the first ten league games of the following campaign, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was once again an ever-present in the squad, featuring in all the outings, starting eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/136865/ricardo-rodriguez-?cc=5901 |title=Ricardo Rodriguez Bio |publisher=ESPNFC | accessdate = 7 May 2013}}</ref> But Magath was sacked after a poor run of form in the league and when [[Lorenz-G<U+00FC>nther K<U+00F6>stner]] was installed as interim manager, the more experienced [[Marcel Sch<U+00E4>fer]] was preferred at left back.<ref name="Sky Sports" /> Once [[Dieter Hecking]] was appointed manager though, Rodr<U+00ED>guez won his place back in the first team.<ref name="Sky Sports" />

==== 2013<U+2013>14 season====
On 9 November 2013, he scored his first goal for Wolfsburg, from a direct [[Direct free kick|free kick]] in a home Bundesliga match against [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/291041/report |title=Wolfsburg trip up Dortmund |work=Sky Sports |date=9 November 2013 |accessdate=18 September 2014 }}</ref> The match ended in a 2<U+2013>1 win for Wolfsburg, although they were losing at half-time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolfsburg vs. Borussia Dortmund|url=http://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/11/09/germany/bundesliga/vfl-wolfsburg/bv-borussia-09-dortmund/1487128/|newspaper=Soccerway|date=9 November 2013}}</ref> His second goal for Wolfsburg came from the [[Penalty kick|penalty spot]] against [[Hamburger SV|Hamburg]] on 29 November, earning his side a 1<U+2013>1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/304843/report |title=Wolfsburg hang on for point |work=Sky Sports |date=29 November 2013 |accessdate=18 September 2014 }}</ref> He opened the scoring in their Bundesliga match on 14 December, curling the ball past keeper [[Sven Ulreich]], as Wolfsburg won 3<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/291103/report |title=Home comforts for Wolfsburg |work=Sky Sports |date=14 December 2013 |accessdate=18 September 2014 }}</ref> 

He finished the 2013<U+2013>14 season with five league goals, in addition to nine assists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scorer|url=http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/scorer/|publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="Four Four Two" /> He failed to make it into the [[2013<U+2013>14 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] Team of the Season, but was included in a list of the Best Defenders for the 2013<U+2013>14 campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga-tv/inc/video_flv/interview/0000290220.inc.php |title=Team of the Season: Defenders |work=Bundesliga |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> Rodr<U+00ED>guez's nine assists also meant that he created more goals than any other full-back in Europe.<ref name="FFT">{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/my/features/how-full-backs-are-making-world-cup-brilliant-and-why-england-need-more-theirs |title=How full-backs are making this World Cup brilliant |work=Four Four Two |date=19 June 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> His impressive displays during the season included 2.3 key passes per game, the same number as [[Andrea Pirlo]], the two-time reigning [[Serie A Footballer of the Year]], and 2.6 successful dribbles per game, more than [[Cristiano Ronaldo]], the reigning [[2013 FIFA Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/the-triangle/soccer-players-you-need-to-know-before-the-world-cup-ricardo-rodriguez/ |title=World Cup Players to Know: Switzerland<U+2019>s Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Grantland |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

====2014<U+2013>15 season====
He scored his first ever goal in [[UEFA competitions|European football]] for Wolfsburg on 18 September 2014, netting directly from a free-kick after having previously scored an own-goal in a 4<U+2013>1 defeat to [[Premier League|English]] side [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29240782 |title=Everton marked their Europa League return with a dominant victory over Germans Wolfsburg at Goodison Park. |work=BBC Sport |date=18 September 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2014 }}</ref> Three days later, Rodriguez scored twice more for Wolfsburg, once from the penalty spot and a volley from a [[Kevin De Bruyne]] corner, as Wolfsburg defeated [[Bayer Leverkusen]] 4<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/german-bundesliga/story/2048154/wolfsburg-cruise-to-4-1-win-against-10-man-bayer-leverkusen |title=Wolfsburg cruise against 10-man Bayer Leverkusen |work=ESPNFC |date=21 September 2014 |accessdate=1 September 2014 }}</ref> He scored his third [[2014<U+2013>15 Bundesliga|league]] goal of the season against [[Werder Bremen]] on 27 September, converting a De Bruyne cross to put the Wolfsburg up 1<U+2013>0 in an eventual 2<U+2013>1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11881/9492866/wolfsburg-hit-back |title=Wolfsburg hit back |work=Sky Sports |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=27 September 2014 }}</ref>

In October 2014, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was ruled out for a number of weeks with a troubled patella tendon and thigh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/injuries-trouble-wolfsburg-kramer-returns-for-gladbach/a-18010950 |title=Injuries trouble Wolfsburg, Kramer returns for Gladbach |work=DW |date=23 October 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014 }}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Lionel Messi (L), Ricardo Rodriguez (R) - Switzerland vs. Argentina, 29th February 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Rodr<U+00ED>guez marking [[Lionel Messi]] in a friendly against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in 2012]]
In 2009, he was part of the [[Switzerland national under-17 football team|Swiss U17 team]] who won the [[2009 FIFA U-17 World Cup]].<ref name="Bundesliga" /> His first goal of the tournament came in Switzerland's second [[2009_FIFA_U-17_World_Cup#Group_B|group game]] against [[Japan national under-17 football team|Japan]] on 27 October 2009, netting the winning goal as the match ended 4<U+2013>3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/nigeria2009/matches/round=253807/match=300102242/report.html |title=Switzerland 4:3 Japan |work=FIFA |date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He opened the scoring for the Swiss in the 35th minute against [[Germany_national_youth_football_team#Germany_national_under-17_squad|Germany]] in the Round of 16 as Switzerland eventually won 4<U+2013>3 in [[Association_football#Duration_and_tie-breaking_methods|added extra time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/nigeria2009/matches/round=253829/match=300102218/report.html |title=Switzerland 4:3 Germany |work=FIFA |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> In the [[2009_FIFA_U-17_World_Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals]] against [[Colombia national under-17 football team|Colombia]], he scored Switzerland's final goal of their 4<U+2013>0 win to reach their first final of a [[FIFA]] competition since a 3<U+2013>0 loss to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in the [[Football_at_the_1924_Summer_Olympics#Gold_medal_match|1924 Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/nigeria2009/matches/round=253825/match=300102256/summary.html |title=Swiss steamroll into first final |work=FIFA |date=12 November 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He played the entire final against [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria]] on 15 November, helping Switzerland to a 1<U+2013>0 victory to become just the third European nation to lift the trophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=920266.html |title=Switzerland lift Under-17 World Cup |work=UEFA |date=15 November 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

Rodr<U+00ED>guez made his debut for [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in a [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group G|qualifying match]] against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 7 October 2011, replacing [[Xherdan Shaqiri]] in the second half of the 0<U+2013>2 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/15220955 |title=Euro 2012: Wales 2<U+2013>0 Switzerland |work=BBC Sport |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/matches/2011/10/07/europe/european-championship-qualification/wales/switzerland/922681/ |title=Wales vs. Switzerland 2<U+2013>0 |work=Soccerway |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref name="FIFA Profile">{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player=313559/profile-detail.html |title=Ricardo Rodriguez <U+2013> Profile |work=FIFA |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> In his full debt four days later, Rodr<U+00ED>guez played the entire match as the Swiss defeated [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] 2<U+2013>0 to end their qualification campaign on a high, despite missing out on a playoff spot to the Balkan side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002284/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Switzerland end on a high against Montenegro |work=UEFA |date=11 October 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/oct/11/switzerland-montenegro-euro-2012-group-g |title=Much-changed Montenegro are beaten by Switzerland |work=The Guardian |date=11 October 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> In a [[Exhibition_game#International_football|friendly]] match against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] on 11 November, he played the entire match as the Swiss kept a clean sheet in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/friendlies/season=2012/matches/round=2000293/match=2008794/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Netherlands draw blank against Switzerland |work=UEFA |date=11 November 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

He played all three matches for Switzerland at the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's tournament|2012 Olympics]], in which they were eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=oly&id=8225397 |title=Mexico into men's Olympic football quarterfinals |work=ESPN |date=2 August 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2014 }}</ref>

Rodr<U+00ED>guez featured in nine of ten [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification <U+2013> UEFA Group E|World Cup qualifying matches]] for the Swiss, totaling 810 minutes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.soccerway.com/players/ricardo-rodriguez/95797/ |title=R. Rodriguez <U+2013> WC Qualification Europe <U+2013> 2014 Brazil <U+2013> Minutes played |work=Soccerway |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> as they qualified for the World Cup with a game to spare, thanks to a 2<U+2013>1 win over [[Albania national football team|Albania]] on 11 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2013/m=10/news=switzerland-route-brazil-2195217.html |title=Switzerland's route to Brazil |work=FIFA |date=11 October 2013 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/253665/report |title=World Cup qualifier: Switzerland book World Cup spot with 2<U+2013>1 win over Albania |work=Sky Sports |date=11 October 2013 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> On 13 May 2014, Rodr<U+00ED>guez was named in Switzerland's squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27391728|title=World Cup 2014: Pajtim Kasami on standby for Switzerland|date=13 May 2014|accessdate=14 May 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> In their opening group game against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] on 15 June, he took the corner which was headed by [[Admir Mehmedi]] for the equaliser, as well as crossing for [[Haris Seferovi<U+0107>]] to score the winner in a 2<U+2013>1 victory.<ref>{{cite news|title=Switzerland 2<U+2013>1 Ecuador|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285085|accessdate=15 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 June 2014}}</ref> During the tournament finals in Brazil, he averaged 5 tackles and 2.5 interceptions per game, earning plaudits for his strong tackling as well as his ability to read the game.<ref name="Four Four Two" />

==Playing style==
Rodr<U+00ED>guez is known for being equally adept at defending as he is going forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/worldcup2014/article-2658116/Switzerland-vs-Ecuador-All-stats-facts-team-news-game-group-E.html |title=Switzerland vs Ecuador: All the stats, facts and team news for the first game in group E |work=Daily Mail |date=14 June 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> Experts consider him as an accomplished defender and note his strong heading ability.<ref name="Sky Sports" /> As well as considering him a continual attacking threat and noting his exceptional stamina and pace which allow for his constant, buccaneering runs up the wing.<ref name="Sky Sports" /><ref name="Four Four Two" /><ref name="FFT" /> Conversely, he has been criticized for giving too much room to opposition attackers, taking up poor positioning and lacking in defensive discipline.<ref name="Four Four Two" /> While other experts have criticized his concentration on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/player/97381/ricardo-rodriguez |title=Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

He has become known for his pinpoint crossing and accurate left foot and has been compared to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[England national football team|England]] left back [[Leighton Baines]].<ref name="FIFA Profile" /><ref name="FFT" /><ref name="Bleacher Report Scouting" /> He is also noted for his speciality in dead ball situations and for penalty taking abilities, emerging as Wolfsburg's first-choice penalty taker during the [[2013<U+2013>14 VfL Wolfsburg season|2013<U+2013>14 season]].<ref name="Bundesliga" /><ref name="Four Four Two" />

==Personal life==
Rodr<U+00ED>guez was born in [[Z<U+00FC>rich]] to a Spanish father and a Chilean mother.<ref name="Bundesliga">{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/liga/news/2012/0000217379.php |title=Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Bundesliga |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> As a result, he is fluent in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and holds [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[Chile|Chilean]] nationalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcz.ch/de/profis/portraits.htm?saison_id=11&id=995 |title=Portraits: Ricardo Rodr<U+00ED>guez  |work=FC Z<U+00FC>rich |accessdate=26 September 2014 |language=German }}</ref><ref name="Bundesliga" /><ref name="Sky Sports">{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/15198/8615777/sky-sports-scout-ricardo-rodriguez |title=Sky Sports Scout <U+2013> Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Sky Sports |date=21 May 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref> He is the younger brother of [[FC St. Gallen]] [[midfielder]] [[Roberto Rodriguez (Swiss footballer)|Roberto Rodr<U+00ED>guez]] and the older brother of [[FC Z<U+00FC>rich]] and [[Switzerland national under-19 football team|Switzerland U19]] midfielder [[Francisco Rodriguez (footballer, born 1995)|Francisco Rodr<U+00ED>guez]].<ref name="Four Four Two">{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/everything-you-need-know-about-ricardo-rodriguez |title=Everything you need to know about... Ricardo Rodriguez |work=Four Four Two |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 }}</ref>

